          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do I choose my North Star Metric?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>A valid NSM must satisfy three criteria: it reflects customer value (not just company revenue), it predicts retention and long-term growth, and it is measurable and actionable by your team. Test 2-3 candidate metrics for 30 days and measure which correlates strongest with retention.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can a company have more than one North Star Metric?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Ideally not. The value of an NSM comes from singular focus. Some companies maintain one primary NSM and 2-3 supporting input metrics, but the moment you have multiple 'north stars', the alignment benefit disappears.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How often should the North Star Metric change?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Rarely — ideally once every 12-18 months at most. Frequent changes prevent momentum from building and make trend analysis meaningless. The metric typically evolves as the business moves from growth to retention phases.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is revenue a good North Star Metric?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Usually not. Revenue is an outcome, not a measure of customer value. A team optimising for revenue can hit their number while customers churn. An NSM should measure the value customers get, which then predicts revenue — not the revenue itself.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

